Wk24 Cell cycle and cell death; epithelial regeneration 

Sunday, September 10, 2017 

1:17 PM 

Describe the normal cell cycle and its regulation 

Normal cell cycle: G1 (metabolically active + duplicated organelles + centrosome replication begins), S (DNA replicates), G2 (centrosomes complete, proteins synthesised), M, G0 (exit from cell cycle) 

 

The restriction point (R) is in G1, and at this point commitment to mitosis occurs and the cell no longer requires growth factors to complete the cell cycle. Cells lose the ability to return to G0, and they begin to undergo DNA synthesis and replication. 

 

Checks occur at the end of G1, G2, and during M.  

 

Describe the normal regeneration of colonic (and other intestinal) epithelium from stem cells 

Small populations of adult stem cells are responsible for the ability of the epithelial lining of the intestine to be efficiently renewed and repaired through life. Persistent aggression from the luminal content on the epithelial cells induces a high rate of death and self-renewal.  

 

LGR5+ crypt base columnar (CBC) stem cells are intercalated with Paneth cells at the crypt base. These cells generate proliferating transit-amplifying TA cells, which occupy the remainder of the crypt. TA cells differentiate into various cells to replace the epithelial cells being lost via anoikis at the villus tip. The +4 reserve stem cells occupying the fourth position from the crypt base can restore the LGR5+ CBC stem cells after injury. 

 

A similar cycle occurs in the colon. The small intestine as an epithelial turnover every 3-5 days whilst the colon has a turnover of 5-7 days.  

 

 

 

Note that the ability for these stem cells to indefinitely self-renew while generating new functional epithelia make stem cells prime candidates for accumulating mutations that promote cancer growth. 

 

Describe the normal non-injury process of cell death in the maintenance of tissue homeostasis 

Cells sense their location within a tissue through specific interactions with neighboring cells and the extracellular matrix. The communication between proximal cells via cell-cell adhesion as well as between cells and the ECM via cell-matrix adhesion provides essential signals for cell growth and survival. Inappropriate cell/ECM reactions lead to a form of apoptosis known as anoikis.  

 

An example of this is anoikis at the villus tip of the small bowel which prevents excessive proliferation of cells and growth of the villus. 

 

Describe the points in the cell cycle where malfunction can result in uncontrolled mitosis 

G1-S (Can DNA synthesis begin?): If the environment (eg nutrient supply) is unfavourable, or there are faults in the DNA, the cell must be restricted from mitosis. 

G2-M (Can the cell commit to mitosis?): If the DNA hasn't been correctly replicated, the cell must be restricted from mitosis. 

M (Spindle checkpoint): Cell stops during M stage if the chromosomes aren't properly attached to the spindle/aligned. 

 

Describe the relationship of mitotic rate to cancer risk (ie epithelial cancers, childhood cancers) 

When there is increased cell division or decreased apoptosis, we have increased risk of cancer. When a cell mutates, high mitotic rate allows it to reproduce further mutated cells before it undergoes apoptosis. This cycle then repeats itself with each of the mutated cells, with further mutation possible. Hence, the number of mutations in a cell can build up and eventually result in cancer.  

 

Describe the six hallmarks of a cancer cell 

 

Sustaining proliferating signaling 

Cancer cells are able to secrete their own growth factors, and are thus independent from the normal regulation by growth-stimulatory signals. Mutations to proto-oncogenes that are a part of the normal growth cascade pathway (eg production of hyperactive RAS oncogene) can allow for signaling by oneself.  

 

 

Evading growth suppressors 

Cancer cells become insensitive to anti-growth signals, and mutations can switch off/inactivate tumour suppression genes. Cell contact inhibition is also lost, with an absence of anoikis to control cell growth.  

 

Evading apoptosis 

Cancer cells can cause the upregulation of anti-apoptotic proteins and downregulation of pro-apoptotic proteins.  

 

Enabling replicative immortality 

Cancer cells activate the telomerase enzyme to acquire limitless replicative potential.  

 

Inducing angiogenesis 

Cancer cells secrete angiogenic factors eg VEGF that stimulate angiogenesis, in order to supply themselves with glucose, oxygen, etc, and evacuate metabolic wastes such as CO2. Hypoxia leads to either cell death or adaptation. If cell populations survive, they have a powerful growth advantage and acquire a motile cell phenotype.

Carcinomas are from epithelial cells. >90% of cancers are from epithelial cells. 

 

Proto-oncogenes are responsible for promoting cell division, driving cells from G1 to S.
